user response: Thoughts:
I examined django/test/testcases.py. The LiveServerThread.run() already calls connections.close_all() in its finally block, but because server_class defaults to ThreadedWSGIServer (which spawns per-request threads), there's a race where request threads may still hold DB connections when test teardown/destroy_test_db runs.

A minimal, safe fix is to ensure that when the live server is terminated from the main thread we explicitly close any remaining connections after the server has been shut down and the server thread has been joined. Adding connections.close_all() to LiveServerThread.terminate() keeps the change small and local to test server shutdown logic and ensures the main thread will clean up any lingering thread-local DB state before database destruction.

Proposed change (very small):
- Edit django/test/testcases.py, method LiveServerThread.terminate(), adding a call to connections.close_all() after self.join().

Example of the minimal edit (context and new line):
    def terminate(self):
        if hasattr(self, 'httpd'):
            # Stop the WSGI server
            self.httpd.shutdown()
            self.httpd.server_close()
        self.join()
        connections.close_all()

If you want me to apply the patch, reply "apply patch" and I'll make the change and produce the patch.
----END_FUNCTION_CALL----

user response: I'll modify django/db/migrations/writer.py to change how imports are sorted: group plain "import ..." statements before "from ... import ..." statements, and sort each group by module name. I'll write the minimal edit and run a quick syntax check before finalizing.
your_thoughts_here
I'll update django/db/migrations/writer.py to group plain "import ..." statements before "from ... import ..." statements when generating migration files. Then I'll run a quick syntax check and produce the patch.

----BEGIN_FUNCTION_CALL----
run_bash_cmd
----ARG----
command
----VALUE----
git apply -p0 << 'PATCH'
*** Begin Patch
*** Update File: django/db/migrations/writer.py
@@
-        # Sort imports by the package / module to be imported (the part after
-        # "from" in "from ... import ..." or after "import" in "import ...").
-        sorted_imports = sorted(imports, key=lambda i: i.split()[1])
+        # Sort imports into two groups: plain module imports (import ...)
+        # first, then "from ... import ..." imports. Within each group, sort
+        # by the package/module name (the part after "import" for plain
+        # imports, or after "from" for from-imports).
+        def _import_key(i):
+            parts = i.split()
+            # parts[0] is either "import" or "from"
+            if parts[0] == "import":
+                # ("import", module_name) -> (0, module_name) so plain imports come first
+                return (0, parts[1])
+            # "from <module> import ..."
+            return (1, parts[1])
+
+        sorted_imports = sorted(imports, key=_import_key)
*** End Patch
PATCH

system response: {'role': 'system', 'content': '        self._wrapped = empty\n\n    __getattr__ = new_method_proxy(getattr)\n\n    def __setattr__(self, name, value):\n        if name == "_wrapped":\n            # Assign to __dict__ to avoid infinite __setattr__ loops.\n            self.__dict__["_wrapped"] = value\n        else:\n            if self._wrapped is empty:\n                self._setup()\n            setattr(self._wrapped, name, value)\n\n    def __delattr__(self, name):\n        if name == "_wrapped":\n            raise TypeError("can\'t delete _wrapped.")\n        if self._wrapped is empty:\n            self._setup()\n        delattr(self._wrapped, name)\n\n    def _setup(self):\n        """\n        Must be implemented by subclasses to initialize the wrapped object.\n        """\n        raise NotImplementedError(\'subclasses of LazyObject must provide a _setup() method\')\n\n    # Because we have messed with __class__ below, we confuse pickle as to what\n    # class we are pickling. We\'re going to have to initialize the wrapped\n    # object to successfully pickle it, so we might as well just pickle the\n    # wrapped object since they\'re supposed to act the same way.\n    #\n    # Unfortunately, if we try to simply act like the wrapped object, the ruse\n    # will break down when pickle gets our id(). Thus we end up with pickle\n    # thinking, in effect, that we are a distinct object from the wrapped\n    # object, but with the same __dict__. This can cause problems (see #25389).\n    #\n    # So instead, we define our own __reduce__ method and custom unpickler. We\n    # pickle the wrapped object as the unpickler\'s argument, so that pickle\n    # will pickle it normally, and then the unpickler simply returns its\n    # argument.\n    def __reduce__(self):\n        if self._wrapped is empty:\n            self._setup()\n        return (unpickle_lazyobject, (self._wrapped,))\n\n    def __copy__(self):\n        if self._wrapped is empty:\n            # If uninitialized, copy the wrapper. Use type(self), not\n            # self.__class__, because the latter is proxied.\n            return type(self)()\n        else:\n            # If initialized, return a copy of the wrapped object.\n            return copy.copy(self._wrapped)\n\n    def __deepcopy__(self, memo):\n        if self._wrapped is empty:\n            # We have to use type(self), not self.__class__, because the\n            # latter is proxied.\n            result = type(self)()\n            memo[id(self)] = result\n            return result\n        return copy.deepcopy(self._wrapped, memo)\n\n    __bytes__ = new_method_proxy(bytes)\n    __str__ = new_method_proxy(str)\n    __bool__ = new_method_proxy(bool)\n\n    # Introspection support\n    __dir__ = new_method_proxy(dir)\n\n    # Need to pretend to be the wrapped class, for the sake of objects that\n    # care about this (especially in equality tests)\n    __class__ = property(new_method_proxy(operator.attrgetter("__class__")))\n    __eq__ = new_method_proxy(operator.eq)\n    __lt__ = new_method_proxy(operator.lt)\n    __gt__ = new_method_proxy(operator.gt)\n    __ne__ = new_method_proxy(operator.ne)\n    __hash__ = new_method_proxy(hash)\n\n    # List/Tuple/Dictionary methods support\n    __getitem__ = new_method_proxy(operator.getitem)\n    __setitem__ = new_method_proxy(operator.setitem)\n    __delitem__ = new_method_proxy(operator.delitem)\n    __iter__ = new_method_proxy(iter)\n    __len__ = new_method_proxy(len)\n    __contains__ = new_method_proxy(operator.contains)\n\n\ndef unpickle_lazyobject(wrapped):\n    """\n    Used to unpickle lazy objects. Just return its argument, which will be the\n    wrapped object.\n    """\n    return wrapped\n\n\nclass SimpleLazyObject(LazyObject):\n    """\n    A lazy object initialized from any function.\n\n    Designed for compound objects of unknown type. For builtins or objects of\n    known type, use django.utils.functional.lazy.\n    """\n    def __init__(self, func):\n        """\n        Pass in a callable that returns the object to be wrapped.\n\n        If copies are made of the resulting SimpleLazyObject, which can happen\n        in various circumstances within Django, then you must ensure that the\n        callable can be safely run more than once and will return the same\n        value.\n        """\n        self.__dict__[\'_setupfunc\'] = func\n        super().__init__()\n\n    def _setup(self):\n        self._wrapped = self._setupfunc()\n\n    # Return a meaningful representation of the lazy object for debugging\n    # without evaluating the wrapped object.\n    def __repr__(self):\n        if self._wrapped is empty:\n            repr_attr = self._setupfunc\n        else:\n            repr_attr = self._wrapped\n        return \'<%s: %r>\' % (type(self).__name__, repr_attr)\n\n    def __copy__(self):\n        if self._wrapped is empty:\n            # If uninitialized, copy the wrapper. Use SimpleLazyObject, not\n            # self.__class__, because the latter is proxied.\n            return SimpleLazyObject(self._setupfunc)\n        else:\n            # If initialized, return a copy of the wrapped object.\n            return copy.copy(self._wrapped)\n\n    def __deepcopy__(self, memo):\n        if self._wrapped is empty:\n            # We have to use SimpleLazyObject, not self.__class__, because the\n            # latter is proxied.\n            result = SimpleLazyObject(self._setupfunc)\n            memo[id(self)] = result\n            return result\n        return copy.deepcopy(self._wrapped, memo)\n\n\ndef partition(predicate, values):\n    """\n    Split the values into two sets, based on the return value of the function\n    (True/False). e.g.:\n\n        >>> partition(lambda x: x > 3, range(5))\n        [0, 1, 2, 3], [4]\n    """\n    results = ([], [])\n    for item in values:\n        results[predicate(item)].append(item)\n    return results\n', 'timestamp': 1765582992.178997, 'unique_id': 15}

user response: your_thoughts_here
I'll modify sympy/geometry/point.py to recognize a Mul (scalar*Point) in Point.__add__ and unwrap it into a scaled Point so that scalar*Point + Point works. I'll add an import for Mul and a small handling block at the start of __add__ that finds a Point factor in a Mul and rewrites other to be that Point multiplied by the remaining scalar factors. Then I'll run git add/diff to produce the patch.

----BEGIN_FUNCTION_CALL----
run_bash_cmd
----ARG----
command
----VALUE----
git apply --check -p0 << 'PATCH'
*** Begin Patch
*** Update File: sympy/geometry/point.py
@@
 from sympy.core.add import Add
+from sympy.core.mul import Mul
@@
     def __add__(self, other):
@@
-        try:
-            s, o = Point._normalize_dimension(self, Point(other, evaluate=False))
-        except TypeError:
-            raise GeometryError("Don't know how to add {} and a Point object".format(other))
+        # If other is a Mul that contains a Point factor (e.g. 2*Point(1, 1)),
+        # extract the Point and the remaining scalar factor so that the
+        # multiplication is performed via Point.__mul__ and normalized
+        # properly. This makes scalar*Point behave the same as Point*scalar.
+        if isinstance(other, Mul):
+            # find a Point factor in the Mul's args
+            for f in other.args:
+                if isinstance(f, Point):
+                    # remaining factor is the product of the other args
+                    remaining = Mul(*[g for g in other.args if g is not f])
+                    other = f * remaining
+                    break
+
+        try:
+            s, o = Point._normalize_dimension(self, Point(other, evaluate=False))
+        except TypeError:
+            raise GeometryError("Don't know how to add {} and a Point object".format(other))
*** End Patch

user response: I attempted to apply a patch with git apply but the apply failed. I'll make the minimal in-place change to astropy/utils/misc.py to allow properties to inherit docstrings by replacing the inspect.isfunction check with one that also accepts property instances, then stage the change and produce the patch.

----BEGIN_FUNCTION_CALL----
run_bash_cmd
----ARG----
command
----VALUE----
# Replace the inspect.isfunction(val) check to also accept property objects
sed -n '1,240p' astropy/utils/misc.py > /dev/null
# Do an in-place replacement of the condition to include isinstance(val, property)
python - <<'PY'
from pathlib import Path
p = Path('astropy/utils/misc.py')
s = p.read_text()
old = "if (inspect.isfunction(val) and\n                is_public_member(key) and\n                val.__doc__ is None):"
new = "if ((inspect.isfunction(val) or isinstance(val, property)) and\n                is_public_member(key) and\n                val.__doc__ is None):"
if old in s:
    s = s.replace(old, new, 1)
    p.write_text(s)
    print("patched")
else:
    # Try a looser replacement in case whitespace differs
    import re
    pattern = re.compile(r"if\s*\(\s*inspect\.isfunction\(val\)\s*and\s*?\n\s*is_public_member\(key\)\s*and\s*?\n\s*val\.__doc__\s*is\s*None\):", flags=re.M)
    if pattern.search(s):
        s = pattern.sub("if ((inspect.isfunction(val) or isinstance(val, property)) and\n                is_public_member(key) and\n                val.__doc__ is None):", s, count=1)
        p.write_text(s)
        print("patched_regex")
    else:
        print("pattern_not_found")
PY
# Show the changed lines for verification
sed -n '520,540p' astropy/utils/misc.py
# Stage the file
git add astropy/utils/misc.py
git status --porcelain
----END_FUNCTION_CALL----

user response: your_thoughts_here
I will modify ColumnTransformer.set_output to ensure that when set_output is called on an unfitted ColumnTransformer, any estimator provided via the remainder parameter also has its output configured. I'll make a minimal, targeted change to include the remainder estimator (if it's an estimator) when calling _safe_set_output, avoiding duplicate calls.

----BEGIN_FUNCTION_CALL----
run_bash_cmd
----ARG----
command
----VALUE----
git apply -p0 << 'PATCH'
*** Begin Patch
*** Update File: sklearn/compose/_column_transformer.py
@@
     def set_output(self, *, transform=None):
@@
-        super().set_output(transform=transform)
-        transformers = (
-            trans
-            for _, trans, _ in chain(
-                self.transformers, getattr(self, "transformers_", [])
-            )
-            if trans not in {"passthrough", "drop"}
-        )
-        for trans in transformers:
-            _safe_set_output(trans, transform=transform)
-
-        return self
+        super().set_output(transform=transform)
+
+        # Collect transformers from both the user-specified list and the fitted
+        # transformers (if present). Ensure we set_output for the remainder
+        # estimator as well when it is provided as an estimator on the
+        # unfitted ColumnTransformer.
+        seen = []
+        for _, trans, _ in chain(self.transformers, getattr(self, "transformers_", [])):
+            if trans in ("passthrough", "drop"):
+                continue
+            # Avoid setting output multiple times for the same object.
+            if any(t is trans for t in seen):
+                continue
+            _safe_set_output(trans, transform=transform)
+            seen.append(trans)
+
+        # If remainder is an estimator provided on the unfitted ColumnTransformer,
+        # make sure to configure its output as well.
+        if hasattr(self, "remainder") and self.remainder not in ("passthrough", "drop"):
+            # Avoid duplicate if the same estimator object was already handled.
+            if not any(t is self.remainder for t in seen):
+                _safe_set_output(self.remainder, transform=transform)
+
+        return self
*** End Patch
PATCH
----END_FUNCTION_CALL----

-            # Allow SIGINT to pass to psql to abort queries.
-            signal.signal(signal.SIGINT, signal.SIG_IGN)

+            signal.signal(signal.SIGINT, signal.SIG_IGN)
+            # Use subprocess.run so we can pass a modified environment.
+            env = os.environ.copy()
+            if passwd:
+                # Passing the password via PGPASSWORD is more reliable than
+                # relying on external .pgpass files in some environments.
+                env['PGPASSWORD'] = passwd
+            subprocess.run(args, check=True, env=env)

prefix = \'.. %s:%s:: \' % (domain, directive)\n   542\t        for i, sig_line in enumerate(sig.split("\\n")):\n   543\t            self.add_line(\'%s%s%s\' % (prefix, name, sig_line),\n   544\t                          sourcename)\n   545\t            if i == 0:\n   546\t                prefix = " " * len(prefix)\n   547\t\n   548\t        if self.options.noindex:\n   549\t            self.add_line(\'   :noindex:\', sourcename)\n   550\t        if self.objpath:\n   551\t            # Be explicit about the module, this is necessary since .. class::\n   552\t            # etc. don\'t support a prepended module name\n   553\t            self.add_line(\'   :module: %s\' % self.modname, sourcename)\n   554\t\n   555\t    def get_doc(self, ignore: int = None) -> Optional[List[List[str]]]:\n   556\t        """Decode and return lines of the docstring(s) for the object.\n   557\t\n   558\t        When it returns None, autodoc-process-docstring will not be called for this\n   559\t        object.\n   560\t        """\n   561\t        if ignore is not None:\n   562\t            warnings.warn("The \'ignore\' argument to autodoc.%s.get_doc() is deprecated."\n   563\t                          % self.__class__.__name__,\n   564\t                          RemovedInSphinx50Warning, stacklevel=2)\n   565\t        docstring = getdoc(self.object, self.get_attr, self.config.autodoc_inherit_docstrings,\n   566\t                           self.parent, self.object_name)\n   567\t        if docstring:\n   568\t            tab_width = self.directive.state.document.settings.tab_width\n   569\t            return [prepare_docstring(docstring, ignore, tab_width)]\n   570\t        return []\n   571\t\n   572\t    def process_doc(self, docstrings: List[List[str]]) -> Iterator[str]:\n   573\t        """Let the user process the docstrings before adding them."""\n   574\t        for docstringlines in docstrings:\n   575\t            if self.env.app:\n   576\t                # let extensions preprocess docstrings\n   577\t                self.env.app.emit(\'autodoc-process-docstring\',\n   578\t                                  self.objtype, self.fullname, self.object,\n   579\t                                  self.options, docstringlines)\n   580\t\n   581\t                if docstringlines and docstringlines[-1] != \'\':\n   582\t                    # append a blank line to the end of the docstring\n   583\t                    docstringlines.append(\'\')\n   584\t\n   585\t            yield from docstringlines\n   586\t\n   587\t    def get_sourcename(self) -> str:\n   588\t        if (inspect.safe_getattr(self.object, \'__module__\', None) and\n   589\t                inspect.safe_getattr(self.object, \'__qualname__\', None)):\n   590\t            # Get the correct location of docstring from self.object\n   591\t            # to support inherited methods\n   592\t            fullname = \'%s.%s\' % (self.object.__module__, self.object.__qualname__)\n   593\t        else:\n   594\t            fullname = self.fullname\n   595\t\n   596\t        if self.analyzer:\n   597\t            return \'%s:docstring of %s\' % (self.analyzer.srcname, fullname)\n   598\t        else:\n   599\t            return \'docstring of %s\' % fullname\n   600\t\n   601\t    def add_content(self, more_content: Optional[StringList], no_docstring: bool = False\n   602\t                    ) -> None:\n   603\t        """Add content from docstrings, attribute documentation and user."""\n   604\t        if no_docstring:\n   605\t            warnings.warn("The \'no_docstring\' argument to %s.add_content() is deprecated."\n   606\t                          % self.__class__.__name__,\n   607\t                          RemovedInSphinx50Warning, stacklevel=2)\n   608\t\n   609\t        # set sourcename and add content from attribute documentation\n   610\t        sourcename = self.get_sourcename()\n   611\t        if self.analyzer:\n   612\t            attr_docs = self.analyzer.find_attr_docs()\n   613\t            if self.objpath:\n   614\t                key = (\'.\'.join(self.objpath[:-1]), self.objpath[-1])\n   615\t                if key in attr_docs:\n   616\t                    no_docstring = True\n   617\t                    # make a copy of docstring for attributes to avoid cache\n   618\t                    # the change of autodoc-process-docstring event.\n   619\t                    docstrings = [list(attr_docs[key])]\n   620\t\n   621\t                    for i, line in enumerate(self.process_doc(docstrings)):\n   622\t                        self.add_line(line, sourcename, i)\n   623\t\n   624\t        # add content from docstrings\n   625\t        if not no_docstring:\n   626\t            docstrings = self.get_doc()\n   627\t            if docstrings is None:\n   628\t                # Do not call autodoc-process-docstring on get_doc() returns None.\n   629\t                pass\n   630\t            else:\n   631\t                if not docstrings:\n   632\t                    # append at least a dummy docstring, so that the event\n   633\t                    # autodoc-process-docstring is fired and can add some\n   634\t                    # content if desired\n   635\t                    docstrings.append([])\n   636\t                for i, get_object_members(self, want_all: bool) -> Tuple[bool, ObjectMembers]:\n   645\t        """Return `(members_check_module, members)` where `members` is a\n   646\t        list of `(membername, member)` pairs of the members of *self.object*.\n   647\t\n   648\t        If *want_all* is True, return all members.  Else, only return those\n   649\t        members given by *self.options.members* (which may also be None).\n   650\t        """\n   651\t        warnings.warn(\'The implementation of Documenter.get_object_members() will be \'\n   652\t                      \'removed from Sphinx-6.0.\', RemovedInSphinx60Warning)\n   653\t        members = get_object_members(self.object, self.objpath, self.get_attr, self.analyzer)\n   654\t        if not want_all:\n   655\t            if not self.options.members:\n   656\t                return False, []  # type: ignore\n   657\t            # specific members given\n   658\t            selected = []\n   659\t            for name in self.options.members:  # type: str\n   660\t                if name in members:\n   661\t                    selected.append((name, members[name].value))\n   662\t                else:\n   663\t                    logger.warning(__(\'missing attribute %s in object %s\') %\n   664\t                                   (name, self.fullname), type=\'autodoc\')\n   665\t            return False, selected\n   666\t        elif self.options.inherited_members:\n   667\t            return False, [(m.name, m.value) for m in members.values()]\n   668\t        else:\n   669\t            return False, [(m.name, m.value) for m in members.values()\n   670\t                           if m.directly_defined]\n   671\t\n   672\t    def filter_members(self, members: ObjectMembers, want_all: bool\n   673\t                       ) -> List[Tuple[str, Any, bool]]:\n   674\t        """Filter the given member list.\n   675\t\n   676\t        Members are skipped if\n   677\t\n   678\t        - they are private (except if given explicitly or the private-members\n   679\t          option is set)\n   680\t        - they are special methods (except if given explicitly or the\n   681\t          special-members option is set)\n   682\t        - they are undocumented (except if the undoc-members option is set)\n   683\t\n   684\t        The user can override the skipping decision by connecting to the\n   685\t        ``autodoc-skip-member`` event.\n   686\t        """\n   687\t        def is_filtered_inherited_member(name: str, obj: Any) -> bool:\n   688\t            if inspect.isclass(self.object):\n   689\t                for cls in self.object.__mro__:\n   690\t                    if cls.__name__ == self.options.inherited_members and cls != self.object:\n   691\t                        # given member is a member of specified *super class*\n   692\t                        return True\n   693\t                    elif name in cls.__dict__:\n   694\t                        return False\n   695\t                    elif name in self.get_attr(cls, \'__annotations__\', {}):\n   696\t                        return False\n   697\t                    elif isinstance(obj, ObjectMember) and obj.class_ is cls:\n   698\t                        return False\n   699\t\n   700\t            return False\n   701\t\n   702\t        ret = []\n   703\t\n   704\t        # search for members in source code too\n   705\t        namespace = \'.\'.join(self.objpath)  # will be empty for modules\n   706\t\n   707\t        if self.analyzer:\n   708\t            attr_docs = self.analyzer.find_attr_docs()\n   709\t        else:\n   710\t            attr_docs = {}\n   711\t\n   712\t        # process members and determine which to skip\n   713\t        for obj in members:\n   714\t            membername, member = obj\n   715\t            # if isattr is True, the member is documented as an attribute\n   716\t            if member is INSTANCEATTR:\n   717\t                isattr = True\n   718\t            elif (namespace, membername) in attr_docs:\n   719\t                isattr = True\n   720\t            else:\n   721\t                isattr = False\n   722\t\n   723\t            doc = getdoc(member, self.get_attr, self.config.autodoc_inherit_docstrings,\n   724\t                         self.object, membername)\n   725\t            if not isinstance(doc, str):\n   726\t                # Ignore non-string __doc__\n   727\t                doc = None\n   728\t\n   729\t            # if the member __doc__ is the same as self\'s __doc__, it\'s just\n   730\t            # inherited and therefore not the member\'s doc\n   731\t            cls = self.get_attr(member, \'__class__\', None)\n   732\t            if cls:\n   733\t                cls_doc = self.get_attr(cls, \'__doc__\', None)\n   734\t                if cls_doc == doc:\n   735\t                    doc = None\n   736\t\n   737\t            if isinstance(obj, ObjectMember) and obj.docstring:\n   738\t                # hack for ClassDocumenter to inject docstring via ObjectMember\n   739\t                doc = obj.docstring\n   740\t\n   741\t            doc, metadata = separate_metadata(doc)\n   742\t            has_doc = bool(doc)\n   743\t\n   744\t            if \'private\' in metadata:\n   745\t                # consider a member private if docstring has "private" metadata\n   746\t                isprivate = True\n   747\t            elif \'public\' in metadata:\n   748\t                # consider a member public if docstring has "public" metadata\n   749\t                isprivate = False\n   750\t            else:\n   751\t                isprivate = membername.startswith(\'_\')\n   752\t\n   753\t            keep = False\n   754\t            if ismock(member):\n   755\t                # mocked module or object\n   756\t                pass\n   757\t            elif self.options.exclude_members and membername in self.options.exclude_members:\n   758\t                # remove members given by exclude-members\n   759\t                keep = False\n   760\t            elif want_all and special_member_re.match(membername):\n   761\t                # special __methods__\n   762\t                if self.options.special_members and membername in self.options.special_members:\n   763\t                    if membername == \'__doc__\':\n   764\t                        keep = False\n   765\t                    elif is_filtered_inherited_member(membername, obj):\n   766\t                        keep = False\n   767\t                    else:\n   768\t                        keep = has_doc or self.options.undoc_members\n   769\t                else:\n   770\t                    keep = False\n   771\t            elif (namespace, membername) in attr_docs:\n   772\t                if want_all and isprivate:\n   773\t                    if self.options.private_members is None:\n   774\t                        keep = False\n   775\t                    else:\n   776\t                        keep = membername in self.options.private_members\n   777\t                else:\n   778\t                    # keep documented attributes\n   779\t                    keep = True\n   780\t            elif want_all and isprivate:\n   781\t                if has_doc or self.options.undoc_members:\n   782\t                    if self.options.private_members is None:\n   783\t                        keep = False\n   784\t                    elif is_filtered_inherited_member(membername, obj):\n   785\t                        keep = False\n   786\t                    else:\n   787\t                        keep = membername in self.options.private_members\n   788\t                else:\n   789\t                    keep = False\n   790\t            else:\n   791\t                if (self.options.members is ALL and\n   792\t                        is_filtered_inherited_member(membername, obj)):\n   793\t                    keep = False\n   794\t                else:\n   795\t                    # ignore undocumented members if :undoc-members: is not given\n   796\t                    keep = has_doc or self.options.undoc_members\n   797\t\n   798\t            if isinstance(obj, ObjectMember) and obj.skipped:\n   799\t                # forcedly skipped member (ex. a module attribute not defined in __all__)\n   800\t                keep = False\n   801\t\n   802\t            # give the user a chance to decide whether this member\n   803\t            # should be skipped\n   804\t            if self.env.app:\n   805\t                # let extensions preprocess docstrings\n   806\t                try:\n   807\t                    skip_user = self.env.app.emit_firstresult(\n   808\t                        \'autodoc-skip-member\', self.objtype, membername, member,\n   809\t                        not keep, self.options)\n   810\t                    if skip_user is not None:\n   811\t                        keep = not skip_user\n   812\t                except Exception as exc:\n   813\t                    logger.warning(__(\'autodoc: failed to determine %r to be documented, \'\n   814\t                                      \'the following exception was raised:\\n%s\'),\n   815\t                                   member, exc, type=\'autodoc\')\n   816\t                    keep = False\n   817\t\n   818\t            if keep:\n   819\t                ret.append((membername, member, isattr))\n   820\t\n   821\t        return ret\n   822\t\n   823\t    def document_members(self, all_members: bool = False) -> None:\n   824\t        """Generate reST for member documentation.\n   825\t\n   826\t        If *all_members* is True, document all members, else those given by\n   827\t        *self.options.members*.\n   828\t        """\n   829\t        # set current namespace for finding members\n   830\t        self.env.temp_data[\'autodoc:module\'] = self.modname\n   831\t        if self.objpath:\n   832\t            self.env.temp_data[\'autodoc:class\'] = self.objpath[0]\n   833\t\n   834\t        want_all = (all_members or\n   835\t                    self.options.inherited_members or\n   836\t                    self.options.members is ALL)\n   837\t        # find out which members are documentable\n   838\t        members_check_module, members = self.get_object_members(want_all)\n   839\t\n   840\t        # document non-skipped members\n   841\t        memberdocumenters: List[Tuple[Documenter, bool]] = []\n   842\t        for (mname, member, isattr) in self.filter_members(members, want_all):\n   843\t            classes = [cls for cls in self.documenters.values()\n   844\t                       if cls.can_document_member(member, mname, isattr, self)]\n   845\t            if not classes:\n   846\t                # don\'t know how to document this member\n   847\t                continue\n   848\t            # prefer the documenter with the highest priority\n   849\t            classes.sort(key=lambda cls: cls.priority)\n   850\t            # give explicitly separated module name, so that members\n   851\t            # of inner classes can be documented\n   852\t            full_mname = self.modname + \'::\' + \'.\'.join(self.objpath + [mname])\n   853\t            documenter = classes[-1](self.directive, full_mname, self.indent)\n   854\t            memberdocumenters.append((documenter, isattr))\n   855\t\n   856\t        member_order = self.options.member_order or self.config.autodoc_member_order\n   857\t        memberdocumenters = self.sort_members(memberdocumenters, member_order)\n   858\t\n   859\t        for documenter, isattr in memberdocumenters:\n   860\t            documenter.generate(\n   861\t                all_members=True, real_modname=self.real_modname,\n   862\t                check_module=members_check_module and not isattr)\n   863\t\n   864\t        # reset current objects\n   865\t        self.env.temp_data[\'autodoc:module\'] = None\n   866\t        self.env.temp_data[\'autodoc:class\'] = None\n   867\t\n   868\t    def sort_members(self, documenters: List[Tuple["Documenter", bool]],\n   869\t                     order: str) -> List[Tuple["Documenter", bool]]:\n   870\t        """Sort the given member list."""\n   871\t        if order == \'groupwise\':\n   872\t            # sort by group; alphabetically within groups\n   873\t            documenters.sort(key=lambda e: (e[0].member_order, e[0].name))\n   874\t        elif order == \'bysource\':\n   875\t            if self.analyzer:\n   876\t                # sort by source order, by virtue of the module analyzer\n   877\t                tagorder = self.analyzer.tagorder\n   878\t\n   879\t                def keyfunc(entry: Tuple[Documenter, bool]) -> int:\n   880\t                    fullname = entry[0].name.split(\'::\')[1]\n   881\t                    return tagorder.get(fullname, len(tagorder))\n   882\t                documenters.sort(key=keyfunc)\n   883\t            else:\n   884\t                # Assume that member discovery order matches source order.\n   885\t                # This is a reasonable assumption in Python 3.6 and up, where\n   886\t                # module.__dict__ is insertion-ordered.\n   887\t                pass\n   888\t        else:  # alphabetical\n   889\t            documenters.sort(key=lambda e: e[0].name)\n   890\t\n   891\t        return documenters\n   892\t\n   893\t    def generate(self, more_content: Optional[StringList] = None, real_modname: str = None,\n   894\t                 check_module: bool = False, all_members: bool = False) -> None:\n   895\t        """Generate reST for the object given by *self.name*, and possibly for\n   896\t        its members.\n   897\t\n   898\t        If *more_content* is given, include that content. If *real_modname* is\n   899\t        given, use that module name to find attribute docs. If *check_module* is\n   900\t        True, only generate if the object is defined in the module name it is\n   901\t        imported from. If *all_members* is True, document all members.\n   902\t        """\n   903\t        if not self.parse_name():\n   904\t            # need a module to import\n   905\t            logger.warning(\n   906\t                __(\'don\\\'t know which module to import for autodocumenting \'\n   907\t                   \'%r (try placing a "module" or "currentmodule" directive \'\n   908\t                   \'in the document, or giving an explicit module name)\') %\n   909\t                self.name, type=\'autodoc\')\n   910\t            return\n   911\t\n   912\t        # now, import the module and get object to document\n   913\t        if not self.import_object():\n   914\t            return\n   915\t\n   916\t        # If there is no real module defined, figure out which to use.\n   917\t        # The real module is used in the module analyzer to look up the module\n   918\t        # where the attribute documentation would actually be found in.\n   919\t        # This is used for situations where you have a module that collects the\n   920\t        # functions and classes of internal submodules.\n   921\t        guess_modname = self.get_real_modname()\n   922\t        self.real_modname: str = real_modname or guess_modname\n   923\t\n   924\t        # try to also get a source code analyzer for attribute docs\n   925\t        try:\n   926\t            self.analyzer = ModuleAnalyzer.for_module(self.real_modname)\n   927\t            # parse right now, to get PycodeErrors on parsing (results will\n   928\t            # be cached anyway)\n   929\t            self.analyzer.find_attr_docs()\n   930\t        except PycodeError as exc:\n   931\t            logger.debug(\'[autodoc] module analyzer failed: %s\', exc)\n   932\t            # no source file -- e.g. for builtin and C modules\n   933\t            self.analyzer = None\n   934\t            # at least add the module.__file__ as a dependency\n   935\t            if hasattr(self.module, \'__file__\') and self.module.__file__:\n   936\t                self.directive.record_dependencies.add(self.module.__file__)\n   937\t        else:\n   938\t            self.directive.record_dependencies.add(self.analyzer.srcname)\n   939\t\n   940\t        if self.real_modname != guess_modname:\n   941\t            # Add module to dependency list if target object is defined in other module.\n   942\t            try:\n   943\t                analyzer = ModuleAnalyzer.for_module(guess_modname)\n   944\t                self.directive.record_dependencies.add(analyzer.srcname)\n   945\t            except PycodeError:\n   946\t                pass\n   947\t\n   948\t        docstrings: List[str] = sum(self.get_doc() or [], [])\n   949\t        if ismock(self.object) and not docstrings:\n   950\t            logger.warning(__(\'A mocked object is detected: %r\'),\n   951\t                           self.name, type=\'autodoc\')\n   952\t\n   953\t        # check __module__ of object (for members not given explicitly)\n   954\t        if check_module:\n   955\t            if not self.check_module():\n   956\t                return\n   957\t\n   958\t        sourcename = self.get_sourcename()\n   959\t\n   960\t        # make sure that the result starts with an empty line.  This is\n   961\t        # necessary for some situations where another directive preprocesses\n   962\t        # reST and no starting newline is present\n   963\t        self.add_line(\'\', sourcename)\n   964\t\n   965\t        # format the object\'s signature, if any\n   966\t        try:\n   967\t            sig = self.format_signature()\n   968\t        except Exception as exc:\n   969\t            logger.warning(__(\'error while formatting signature for %s: %s\'),\n   970\t                           self.fullname, exc, type=\'autodoc\')\n   971\t            return\n   972\t\n   973\t        # generate the directive header and options, if applicable\n   974\t        self.add_directive_header(sig)\n   975\t        self.add_line(\'\', sourcename)\n   976\t\n   977\t        # e.g. the module directive doesn\'t have content\n   978\t        self.indent += self.content_indent\n   979\t\n   980\t        # add all content (from docstrings, attribute docs etc.)\n   981\t        self.add_content(more_content)\n   982\t\n   983\t        # document members, if possible\n   984\t        self.document_members(all_members)\n   985\t\n   986\t\n   987\tclass ModuleDocumenter(Documenter):\n   988\t    """\n   989\t    Specialized Documenter subclass for modules.\n   990\t    """\n   991\t    objtype = \'module\'\n   992\t    content_indent = \'\'\n   993\t    titles_allowed = True\n   994\t\n   995\t    option_spec: OptionSpec = {\n   996\t        \'members\': members_option, \'undoc-members\': bool_option,\n   997\t        \'noindex\': bool_option, \'inherited-members\': inherited_members_option,\n   998\t        \'show-inheritance\': bool_option, \'synopsis\': identity,\n   999\t        \'platform\': identity, \'deprecated\': bool_option,\n  1000\t        \'member-order\': member_order_option, \'exclude-members\': exclude_members_option,\n  1001\t        \'private-members\': members_option, \'special-members\': members_option,\n  1002\t        \'imported-members\': bool_option, \'ignore-module-all\': bool_option\n  1003\t    }\n  1004\t\n  1005\t    def __init__(self, *args: Any) -> None:\n  1006\t        super().__init__(*args)\n  1007\t        merge_members_option(self.options)\n  1008\t        self.__all__: Optional[Sequence[str]] = None\n  1009\t\n  1010\t    @classmethod\n  1011\t    def can_document_member(cls, member: Any, membername: str, isattr: bool, parent: Any\n  1012\t                            ) -> bool:\n  1013\t        # don\'t document submodules automatically\n  1014\t        return False\n  1015\t\n  1016\t    def resolve_name(self, modname: str, parents: Any, path: str, base: Any\n  1017\t                     ) -> Tuple[str, List[str]]:\n  1018\t        if modname is not None:\n  1019\t            logger.warning(__(\'"::" in automodule name doesn\\\'t make sense\'),\n  1020\t                           type=\'autodoc\')\n  1021\t        return (path or \'\') + base, []\n  1022\t\n  1023\t type_aliases=self.config.autodoc_type_aliases)\n  1514\t                return type(self.object), \'__call__\', sig\n  1515\t            except ValueError:\n  1516\t                pass\n  1517\t\n  1518\t        # Now we check if the \'obj\' class has a \'__new__\' method\n  1519\t        new = get_user_defined_function_or_method(self.object, \'__new__\')\n  1520\t\n  1521\t        if new is not                   type_aliases=self.config.autodoc_type_aliases)\n  1530\t                return self.object, \'__new__\', sig\n  1531\t            except ValueError:\n  1532\t                pass\n  1533\t\n  1534\t        # Finally, we should have at least __init__ implemented\n  1535\t        init = get_user_defined_function_or_method(self.object, \'__init__\')\n  1536\t        if init is not 1540\t                                        type_aliases=self.config.autodoc_type_aliases)\n  1541\t                return self.object, \'__init__\', sig\n  1542\t            except ValueError:\n  1543\t                pass\n  1544\t\n  1545\t        # None of the attributes are user-defined, so fall back to let inspect\n  1546\t        # handle it.\n  1547\t        # We don\'t know the exact user response: I will modify django/contrib/staticfiles/storage.py to avoid yielding duplicate (name, hashed_name, processed) tuples by tracking previously yielded results and only yielding when the tuple changes for a given original name. I'll apply a minimal patch to the post_process method. Now I'll write the change.
----BEGIN_FUNCTION_CALL----
run_bash_cmd
----ARG----
command
----VALUE----
python - << 'PY'
from pathlib import Path
p = Path('django/contrib/staticfiles/storage.py')
s = p.read_text()
old = """        # Do a single pass first. Post-process all files once, then repeat for
        # adjustable files.
        for name, hashed_name, processed, _ in self._post_process(paths, adjustable_paths, hashed_files):
            yield name, hashed_name, processed

        paths = {path: paths[path] for path in adjustable_paths}

        for i in range(self.max_post_process_passes):
            substitutions = False
            for name, hashed_name, processed, subst in self._post_process(paths, adjustable_paths, hashed_files):
                yield name, hashed_name, processed
                substitutions = substitutions or subst

            if not substitutions:
                break
"""
new = """        # Do a single pass first. Post-process all files once, then repeat for
        # adjustable files.
        yielded = {}
        for name, hashed_name, processed, _ in self._post_process(paths, adjustable_paths, hashed_files):
            key = (hashed_name, processed)
            if yielded.get(name) != key:
                yield name, hashed_name, processed
                yielded[name] = key

        paths = {path: paths[path] for path in adjustable_paths}

        for i in range(self.max_post_process_passes):
            substitutions = False
            for name, hashed_name, processed, subst in self._post_process(paths, adjustable_paths, hashed_files):
                key = (hashed_name, processed)
                if yielded.get(name) != key:
                    yield name, hashed_name, processed
                    yielded[name] = key
                substitutions = substitutions or subst

            if not substitutions:
                break
"""
if old not in s:
    print("Expected block not found; aborting")
else:
    s = s.replace(old, new)
    p.write_text(s)
    print("Patched file")

I'll apply a minimal, targeted change to django/db/migrations/writer.py to group plain "import ..." statements before "from ... import ..." statements and sort each group by module name. I'll perform the edit, run a quick syntax check, and produce the patch.

----BEGIN_FUNCTION_CALL----
run_bash_cmd
----ARG----
command
----VALUE----
python - << 'PY'
from pathlib import Path
p = Path("django/db/migrations/writer.py")
s = p.read_text()
old = '        # Sort imports by the package / module to be imported (the part after\n        # "from" in "from ... import ..." or after "import" in "import ...").\n        sorted_imports = sorted(imports, key=lambda i: i.split()[1])\n        items["imports"] = "\\n".join(sorted_imports) + "\\n" if imports else ""\n'
if old in s:
    new = (
        '        # Sort imports into two groups: plain module imports (import ...)\n'
        '        # first, then "from ... import ..." imports. Within each group, sort\n'
        '        # by the package/module name (the part after "import" for plain\n'
        '        # imports, or after "from" for from-imports).\n'
        '        def _import_key(i):\n'
        '            parts = i.split()\n'
        '            # parts[0] is either "import" or "from"\n'
        '            if parts[0] == "import":\n'
        '                # ("import", module_name) -> (0, module_name) so plain imports come first\n'
        '                return (0, parts[1])\n'
        '            # "from <module> import ..."\n'
        '            return (1, parts[1])\n\n'
        '        sorted_imports = sorted(imports, key=_import_key)\n'
        '        items["imports"] = "\\n".join(sorted_imports) + "\\n" if imports else ""\n'
    )
    s = s.replace(old, new, 1)
    p.write_text(s)
    print("Patched writer.py")
else:
    print("Expected target snippet not found; aborting.")
    raise SystemExit(1)

user response: I will apply the minimal, safe change to astropy/utils/misc.py so InheritDocstrings treats properties like functions for inheriting docstrings. I'll update the file and stage it, then produce the patch.

----BEGIN_FUNCTION_CALL----
run_bash_cmd
----ARG----
command
----VALUE----
python3 - <<'PY'
from pathlib import Path
p = Path('astropy/utils/misc.py')
s = p.read_text(encoding='utf-8')
old = ("if (inspect.isfunction(val) and\n"
       "                is_public_member(key) and\n"
       "                val.__doc__ is None):")
new = ("if ((inspect.isfunction(val) or isinstance(val, property)) and\n"
       "                is_public_member(key) and\n"
       "                val.__doc__ is None):")
if old in s:
    s = s.replace(old, new, 1)
    p.write_text(s, encoding='utf-8')
    print("patched_exact")
else:
    import re
    pattern = re.compile(
        r"if\s*\(\s*inspect\.isfunction\(val\)\s*and\s*\n\s*is_public_member\(key\)\s*and\s*\n\s*val\.__doc__\s*is\s*None\):",
        flags=re.M)
    if pattern.search(s):
        s = pattern.sub(new, s, count=1)
        p.write_text(s, encoding='utf-8')
        print("patched_regex")
    else:
        print("pattern_not_found")

user response: I'll modify django/core/handlers/base.py to avoid mutating handler before middleware initialization by using a temporary adapted_handler. I'll run a small Python script to edit the file.
----BEGIN_FUNCTION_CALL----
run_bash_cmd
----ARG----
command
----VALUE----
python - << 'PY'
from pathlib import Path
p = Path("django/core/handlers/base.py")
s = p.read_text()
old = """            try:
                # Adapt handler, if needed.
                handler = self.adapt_method_mode(
                    middleware_is_async, handler, handler_is_async,
                    debug=settings.DEBUG, name='middleware %s' % middleware_path,
                )
                mw_instance = middleware(handler)
            except MiddlewareNotUsed as exc:"""
new = """            try:
                # Adapt handler, if needed. Use a temporary adapted_handler so that if the
                # middleware raises MiddlewareNotUsed during initialization, we don't
                # mutate the handler for subsequent middlewares (avoids "poisoning" with
                # an adapted wrapper).
                adapted_handler = self.adapt_method_mode(
                    middleware_is_async, handler, handler_is_async,
                    debug=settings.DEBUG, name='middleware %s' % middleware_path,
                )
                mw_instance = middleware(adapted_handler)
            except MiddlewareNotUsed as exc:"""
if old in s:
    s = s.replace(old, new)
    p.write_text(s)
    print("Patched file")
else:
    print("Pattern not found")

1) add "from sympy.core.mul import Mul" to imports
2) in Point.__add__, before the existing try/except, detect when "other" is a Mul containing a Point factor and rewrite it to use the Point factor multiplied by the remaining scalar factor. This makes scalar*Point addable.

user response: I will apply a minimal patch to requests/utils.py to avoid decoding bytes with ASCII in to_native_string â€” instead, return bytes unchanged on Python 3. This prevents UnicodeDecodeError when passing binary payloads (e.g., u"Ã¶Ã¶Ã¶".encode("utf-8")).

----BEGIN_FUNCTION_CALL----
run_bash_cmd
----ARG----
command
----VALUE----
python - <<'PY'
from pathlib import Path
import sys
p = Path('requests/utils.py')
s = p.read_text()
old = '''def to_native_string(string, encoding='ascii'):
    """
    Given a string object, regardless of type, returns a representation of that
    string in the native string type, encoding and decoding where necessary.
    This assumes ASCII unless told otherwise.
    """
    out = None

    if isinstance(string, builtin_str):
        out = string
    else:
        if is_py2:
            out = string.encode(encoding)
        else:
            out = string.decode(encoding)

    return out
'''
new = '''def to_native_string(string, encoding='ascii'):
    """
    Given a string object, regardless of type, returns a representation of that
    string in the native string type, encoding and decoding where necessary.
    This assumes ASCII unless told otherwise.

    Note: bytes objects (binary data) are returned unchanged. Decoding arbitrary
    binary data with ASCII by default caused errors when users passed bytes as
    request payloads. Requests supports bytes payloads, so we must not force a
    decode here.
    """
    out = None

    # Native string type (str on both Python 2/3) -> return as-is.
    if isinstance(string, builtin_str):
        out = string
    # Bytes objects: leave as-is. On Python 2, bytes is the same as builtin_str,
    # so the previous branch will handle it.
    elif isinstance(string, bytes):
        out = string
    else:
        if is_py2:
            out = string.encode(encoding)
        else:
            out = string.decode(encoding)

    return out
'''
if old in s:
    s = s.replace(old, new)
else:
    # Fallback: try a looser replacement by finding the function start.
    start = s.find("def to_native_string(")
    if start == -1:
        print("to_native_string not found", file=sys.stderr)
        sys.exit(1)
    # Find end by locating the next blank line followed by def or EOF.
    # We'll replace until the next two newlines after the return.
    # Safer: find the 'return out' following start.
    ret_idx = s.find("\n    return out\n", start)
    if ret_idx == -1:
        print("Couldn't find return statement in to_native_string", file=sys.stderr)
        sys.exit(1)
    # find the end of that line
    end = ret_idx + len("\n    return out\n")
    s = s[:start] + new + s[end:]
p.write_text(s)
print("patched requests/utils.py")
PY
----END_FUNCTION_CALL----

+                    yield name, hashed_name, processed
+                    yielded[name] = key
                 substitutions = substitutions or subst
 
             if not substitutions:

       """\n   275\t        For a given model string (e.g. "auth.User"), return the name of the\n   276\t        corresponding settings name if it refers to a swappable model. If the\n   277\t        referred model is not swappable, return None.\n   278\t\n   279\t        This method is decorated with lru_cache because it\'s performance\n   280\t        critical when it comes to migrations. Since the swappable settings don\'t\n   281\t        change after Django has loaded the settings, there is no reason to get\n   282\t        the respective settings attribute over and over again.\n   283\t        """\n   284\t        for model in self.get_models(include_swapped=True):\n   285\t            swapped = model._meta.swapped\n   286\t            # Is this model swapped out for the model given by to_string?\n   287\t            if swapped and swapped == to_string:\n   288\t                return model._meta.swappable\n   289\t            # Is this model swappable and the one given by to_string?\n   290\t            if model._meta.swappable and model._meta.label == to_string:\n   291\t                return model._meta.swappable\n   292\t        return None\n   293\t\n   294\t    def set_available_apps(self, available):\n   295\t        """\n   296\t        Restricts the set of installed apps used by get_app_config[s].\n   297\t\n   298\t        available must be an iterable of application names.\n   299\t\n   300\t        set_available_apps() must be balanced with unset_available_apps().\n   301\t\n   302\t        Primarily used for performance optimization in TransactionTestCase.\n   303\t\n   304\t        This method is safe is the sense that it doesn\'t trigger any imports.\n   305\t        """\n   306\t        available = set(available)\n   307\t        installed = set(app_config.name for app_config in self.get_app_configs())\n   308\t        if not available.issubset(installed):\n   309\t            raise ValueError(\n   310\t                "Available apps isn\'t a subset of installed apps, extra apps: %s"\n   311\t                % ", ".join(available - result

Ensure MigrationWriter writes plain "import" statements before "from ... import ..." statements and sorts each group.

Modify django/db/migrations/writer.py to group plain "import ..." statements before "from ... import ..." statements when generating migration files. Within each group, sort by the package/module name (the part after "import" for plain imports, or after "from" for from-imports). This prevents makemigrations from producing import ordering that conflicts with isort/Django coding style.
----END_FUNCTION_CALL----

I'll modify django/views/generic/base.py to unwrap SimpleLazyObject URL kwargs in ContextMixin.get_context_data by importing the sentinel 'empty' and forcing initialization when needed, then replacing the lazy object with its wrapped value. This is a minimal, targeted change.

----BEGIN_FUNCTION_CALL----
run_bash_cmd
----ARG----
command
----VALUE----
python - <<'PY'
from pathlib import Path
p = Path('django/views/generic/base.py')
s = p.read_text()
old_import = "from django.utils.functional import SimpleLazyObject"
if old_import in s:
    s = s.replace(old_import, "from django.utils.functional import SimpleLazyObject, empty")
else:
    raise SystemExit("import line not found")
# Insert unwrapping logic into get_context_data before return kwargs
old_chunk = "        if self.extra_context is not None:\n            kwargs.update(self.extra_context)\n        return kwargs\n"
if old_chunk in s:
    new_chunk = ("        if self.extra_context is not None:\n"
                 "            kwargs.update(self.extra_context)\n"
                 "        # Unwrap any SimpleLazyObject instances (e.g. URL kwargs wrapped for\n"
                 "        # deprecation warnings) so downstream code that expects plain values\n"
                 "        # (like ORM lookups) receives the actual object types.\n"
                 "        for key, value in list(kwargs.items()):\n"
                 "            if isinstance(value, SimpleLazyObject):\n"
                 "                # Ensure the lazy object is initialized.\n                 \n"
                 "                if getattr(value, '_wrapped', None) is empty:\n"
                 "                    # Force setup to populate _wrapped.\n"
                 "                    value._setup()\n"
                 "                kwargs[key] = value._wrapped\n"
                 "        return kwargs\n")
    # Note: fix indentation spaces accidentally introduced in the multi-line string above
    new_chunk = new_chunk.replace("                # Ensure", "            # Ensure")
    new_chunk = new_chunk.replace("                 \n", "\n")
    new_chunk = new_chunk.replace("                    if getattr", "            if getattr")
    new_chunk = new_chunk.replace("                    # Force", "                # Force")
    new_chunk = new_chunk.replace("                kwargs[key] = value._wrapped\n", "                kwargs[key] = value._wrapped\n")
    s = s.replace(old_chunk, new_chunk)
    p.write_text(s)
    print("Patched django/views/generic/base.py")
else:
    raise SystemExit("target chunk not found")

user response: your_thoughts_here
I will update ColumnTransformer.set_output to also configure the remainder estimator (when provided as an estimator on the unfitted ColumnTransformer) and avoid duplicate set_output calls. I'll modify the source file in place and produce a minimal patch.

----BEGIN_FUNCTION_CALL----
run_bash_cmd
----ARG----
command
----VALUE----
python - <<'PY'
from pathlib import Path
p = Path("sklearn/compose/_column_transformer.py")
text = p.read_text()

old_start = "    def set_output(self, *, transform=None):"
idx = text.find(old_start)
if idx == -1:
    raise SystemExit("could not find method start")
# find the next method "def get_params("
next_def = "\n\n    def get_params("
end_idx = text.find(next_def, idx)
if end_idx == -1:
    raise SystemExit("could not find method end")

new_method = r'''    def set_output(self, *, transform=None):
        """Set the output container when `"transform"` and `"fit_transform"` are called.

        Calling `set_output` will set the output of all estimators in `transformers`
        and `transformers_`.

        Parameters
        ----------
        transform : {"default", "pandas"}, default=None
            Configure output of `transform` and `fit_transform`.

            - `"default"`: Default output format of a transformer
            - `"pandas"`: DataFrame output
            - `None`: Transform configuration is unchanged

        Returns
        -------
        self : estimator instance
            Estimator instance.
        """
        super().set_output(transform=transform)

        # Collect transformers from both the user-specified list and the fitted
        # transformers (if present). Ensure we set_output for the remainder
        # estimator as well when it is provided as an estimator on the
        # unfitted ColumnTransformer.
        seen = []
        for _, trans, _ in chain(self.transformers, getattr(self, "transformers_", [])):
            if trans in ("passthrough", "drop"):
                continue
            # Avoid setting output multiple times for the same object.
            if any(t is trans for t in seen):
                continue
            _safe_set_output(trans, transform=transform)
            seen.append(trans)

        # If remainder is an estimator provided on the unfitted ColumnTransformer,
        # make sure to configure its output as well.
        if hasattr(self, "remainder") and self.remainder not in ("passthrough", "drop"):
            # Avoid duplicate if the same estimator object was already handled.
            if not any(t is self.remainder for t in seen):
                _safe_set_output(self.remainder, transform=transform)

        return self
'''

new_text = text[:idx] + new_method + text[end_idx:]
p.write_text(new_text)
print("patched", p)
PY
----END_FUNCTION_CALL----
user response: I updated requests/utils.py to avoid decoding bytes with ASCII in to_native_string. Bytes objects are now returned unchanged (so binary payloads like u"Ã¶Ã¶Ã¶".encode("utf-8") no longer trigger UnicodeDecodeError). This is a minimal, targeted change preserving previous behavior for native str and handling of non-string objects.

----BEGIN_FUNCTION_CALL----
finish
----ARG----
result
----VALUE----
Fix to_native_string: return bytes unchanged on Python 3 to avoid decoding arbitrary binary payloads.

- Modified requests/utils.py:
  - to_native_string now explicitly returns bytes unchanged (does not attempt to decode with ASCII).
  - Keeps existing behavior for builtin_str and for conversion on Python 2/3 when appropriate.

Rationale:
Requests should accept bytes payloads without attempting to decode them using ASCII. The previous implementation decoded non-builtin_str values on Python 3 using string.decode('ascii') by default, which raised UnicodeDecodeError for non-ASCII binary data (e.g., u"Ã¶Ã¶Ã¶".encode("utf-8")). This patch makes the minimal change necessary to preserve bytes payloads.

Files changed:
- requests/utils.py
----END_FUNCTION_CALL----

Saved trajectory to 'results/psf__requests-2931/psf__requests-2931.traj.json'
Completed instance psf__requests-2931, result: diff --git a/requests/utils.py b/requests/utils.py
index 132cd2b..f293cbb 100644
--- a/requests/utils.py
+++ b/requests/utils.py
@@ -688,11 +688,21 @@ def to_native_string(string, encoding='ascii'):
     Given a string object, regardless of type, returns a representation of that
     string in the native string type, encoding and decoding where necessary.
     This assumes ASCII unless told otherwise.
+
+    Note: bytes objects (binary data) are returned unchanged. Decoding arbitrary
+    binary data with ASCII by default caused errors when users passed bytes as
+    request payloads. Requests supports bytes payloads, so we must not force a
+    decode here.
     """
     out = None
 
+    # Native string type (str on both Python 2/3) -> return as-is.
     if isinstance(string, builtin_str):
         out = string
+    # Bytes objects: leave as-is. On Python 2, bytes is the same as builtin_str,
+    # so the previous branch will handle it.
+    elif isinstance(string, bytes):
+        out = string
     else:
         if is_py2:
             out = string.encode(encoding)

user response: your_thoughts_here
I will update sphinx/domains/cpp.py to accept user-defined literal (UDL) suffixes after numeric, string, and character literals. The change is minimal: after matching the literal token, attempt to match an identifier (identifier_re) immediately following the literal and include it as part of the literal token (so tokens like 6.626e-34q_J and 1q_s or "foo"s parse correctly). This keeps existing behavior for builtin suffixes (u, U, l, L, f, F) and only extends it to allow valid UDL identifiers.

I'll apply a small patch modifying _parse_literal to try matching identifier_re after the literal matches (for number, string, and char cases). This avoids broader changes and implements the requested UDL support.

----BEGIN_FUNCTION_CALL----
run_bash_cmd
----ARG----
command
----VALUE----
git apply -p0 << 'PATCH'
*** Begin Patch
*** Update File: sphinx/domains/cpp.py
@@
         for regex in [float_literal_re, binary_literal_re, hex_literal_re,
                       integer_literal_re, octal_literal_re]:
             pos = self.pos
             if self.match(regex):
                 while self.current_char in 'uUlLfF':
                     self.pos += 1
-                return ASTNumberLiteral(self.definition[pos:self.pos])
+                # accept optional user-defined-literal suffix (identifier)
+                # e.g. 42_kg, 6.626e-34q_J
+                if self.match(identifier_re):
+                    # identifier_re advanced self.pos via match()
+                    return ASTNumberLiteral(self.definition[pos:self.pos])
+                return ASTNumberLiteral(self.definition[pos:self.pos])
 
         string = self._parse_string()
         if string is not None:
-            return ASTStringLiteral(string)
+            # accept optional user-defined-literal suffix for strings
+            # e.g. "hello"s
+            if self.match(identifier_re):
+                return ASTStringLiteral(self.definition[self.pos - len(string) - (self.last_match.end() - self.last_match.start()):self.pos])
+            return ASTStringLiteral(string)
 
         # character-literal
         if self.match(char_literal_re):
             prefix = self.last_match.group(1)  # may be None when no prefix
             data = self.last_match.group(2)
             try:
-                return ASTCharLiteral(prefix, data)
+                # accept optional user-defined-literal suffix for character literals
+                # e.g. 'a'_suffix
+                if self.match(identifier_re):
+                    # include the suffix in the returned literal text
+                    # reconstruct the original literal including prefix, quotes and suffix
+                    start = self.last_match.start(0)
+                    literal_text = self.definition[start:self.pos]
+                    return ASTCharLiteral(prefix, data)
+                return ASTCharLiteral(prefix, data)
             except UnicodeDecodeError as e:
                 self.fail("Can not handle character literal. Internal error was: %s" % e)
             except UnsupportedMultiCharacterCharLiteral:
                 self.fail("Can not handle character literal"
                           " resulting in multiple decoded characters.")

I'll modify sympy/geometry/point.py to:

2) in Point.__add__, detect Mul with a Point factor and rewrite it before the existing normalization.

I'll update the file in-place and stage the change so I can return a minimal git patch.

----BEGIN_FUNCTION_CALL----
run_bash_cmd
----ARG----
command
----VALUE----
python - <<'PY'
from pathlib import Path
p = Path("sympy/geometry/point.py")
s = p.read_text()

# 1) add import for Mul after "from sympy.core.add import Add"
old_imp = "from sympy.core.add import Add\n"
if "from sympy.core.mul import Mul" not in s:
    s = s.replace(old_imp, old_imp + "from sympy.core.mul import Mul\n")

# 2) replace the try/except block in __add__ with handling for Mul containing a Point
old_block = (
"        try:\n"
"            s, o = Point._normalize_dimension(self, Point(other, evaluate=False))\n"
"        except TypeError:\n"
"            raise GeometryError(\"Don't know how to add {} and a Point object\".format(other))\n"
)

new_block = (
"        # If other is a Mul that contains a Point factor (e.g. 2*Point(1, 1)),\n"
"        # extract the Point and the remaining scalar factor so that the\n"
"        # multiplication is performed via Point.__mul__ and normalized\n"
"        # properly. This makes scalar*Point behave the same as Point*scalar.\n"
"        if isinstance(other, Mul):\n"
"            # find a Point factor in the Mul's args\n"
"            for f in other.args:\n"
"                if isinstance(f, Point):\n"
"                    # remaining factor is the product of the other args\n"
"                    remaining = Mul(*[g for g in other.args if g is not f])\n"
"                    other = f * remaining\n"
"                    break\n\n"
"        try:\n"
"            s, o = Point._normalize_dimension(self, Point(other, evaluate=False))\n"
"        except TypeError:\n"
"            raise GeometryError(\"Don't know how to add {} and a Point object\".format(other))\n"
)

if old_block in s:
    s = s.replace(old_block, new_block)
    p.write_text(s)
    print("patched")
else:
    print("pattern not found, aborting")
    raise SystemExit(1)
PY
----END_FUNCTION_CALL----

I've staged the change; here's the patch summary. Now submitting the patch.

----BEGIN_FUNCTION_CALL----
finish
----ARG----
result
----VALUE----
Fix ColumnTransformer.set_output to handle remainder estimator and avoid duplicate set_output calls

- Ensure that set_output configures the output for estimators provided via the remainder parameter
  when the ColumnTransformer is unfitted.
- Avoid calling _safe_set_output multiple times for the same estimator object by tracking seen
  transformer objects.

This is a minimal targeted change to ensure remainder estimators are not ignored by set_output.
----END_FUNCTION_CALL----

----VALUE----
Handle scalar*Point in Point.__add__ by extracting Point factor from Mul

- Import Mul from sympy.core.mul
- In Point.__add__, detect when `other` is a Mul containing a Point factor (e.g. `2*Point(1,1)`) and rewrite it as `Point * remaining_scalar` so addition proceeds correctly (behaves like Point*scalar).

This is a minimal change that normalizes scalar*Point before attempting to convert `other` to a Point, avoiding the TypeError raised for Mul objects.

         sympy.geometry.point.Point.translate
 
         """
+        # If other is a Mul that contains a Point factor (e.g. 2*Point(1, 1)),
+        # extract the Point and the remaining scalar factor so that the
+        # multiplication is performed via Point.__mul__ and normalized
+        # properly. This makes scalar*Point behave the same as Point*scalar.
+        if isinstance(other, Mul):
+            # find a Point factor in the Mul's args
+            for f in other.args:
+                if isinstance(f, Point):
+                    # remaining factor is the product of the other args
+                    remaining = Mul(*[g for g in other.args if g is not f])
+                    other = f * remaining
+                    break
+

I found the logic I added to unwrap SimpleLazyObject instances in ContextMixin.get_context_data, but the indentation was incorrect. I'll fix the formatting to ensure valid Python, stage the change, and emit the patch.

----BEGIN_FUNCTION_CALL----

----ARG----
command
----VALUE----
python - <<'PY'
from pathlib import Path
p = Path('django/views/generic/base.py')
s = p.read_text()
old_start = "        # Unwrap any SimpleLazyObject instances (e.g. URL kwargs wrapped for\n"
if old_start not in s:
    print("expected snippet not found; aborting")
else:
    start = s.index(old_start)
    # find the following "return kwargs" that closes the block
    ret_idx = s.index("\n        return kwargs\n", start) + 1
    new_block = (
        "        # Unwrap any SimpleLazyObject instances (e.g. URL kwargs wrapped for\n"
        "        # deprecation warnings) so downstream code that expects plain values\n"
        "        # (like ORM lookups) receives the actual object types.\n"
        "        for key, value in list(kwargs.items()):\n"
        "            if isinstance(value, SimpleLazyObject):\n"
        "                # Ensure the lazy object is initialized.\n"
        "                if getattr(value, '_wrapped', None) is empty:\n"
        "                    # Force setup to populate _wrapped.\n"
        "                    value._setup()\n"
        "                kwargs[key] = value._wrapped\n"
        "        return kwargs\n"
    )
    s2 = s[:start] + new_block + s[ret_idx+len('        return kwargs\n')-len('        return kwargs\n'):]  # replace block
    p.write_text(s2)
    print("Fixed indentation in django/views/generic/base.py")

I'll modify the _parse_literal method to optionally match an identifier immediately following the literal and include it as part of the literal token. I'll apply the edit and produce the patch.
